<i>who were using tracer ammo.</i>

220
00:14:21,639 --> 00:14:24,540
<i>I thought:</i>

221
00:14:24,742 --> 00:14:27,905
<i>"In which other capital in the world,
which is not at war,</i>

222
00:14:28,112 --> 00:14:30,842
<i>can you see something like that?"</i>

223
00:14:31,048 --> 00:14:34,745
Rio de Janeiro is
not in a civil war.

224
00:14:34,952 --> 00:14:38,319
There's a war in the favelas,
between dealers and policemen,

225
00:14:38,523 --> 00:14:41,617
or between dealers
and other dealers.

226
00:14:41,926 --> 00:14:45,555
BOPE'S TRAINING FIELD

227
00:14:55,072 --> 00:14:57,939
FAVELA COMBAT DRILL

228
00:15:04,482 --> 00:15:08,441
<i>During the last 6 months,
100°% of our missions were in favelas.</i>

229
00:15:08,653 --> 00:15:12,521
<i>There were 156 operations
involving confrontation</i>

230
00:15:12,723 --> 00:15:14,816
<i>and maybe the same number
without confrontation.</i>

231
00:15:15,092 --> 00:15:17,822
<i>During confrontations,
we exchanged fire</i>

232
00:15:18,029 --> 00:15:19,826
<i>with heavily armed dealers.</i>

233
00:15:20,031 --> 00:15:22,056
<i>We've acquired an experience
in favela combat</i>

234
00:15:22,266 --> 00:15:24,325
<i>that can't be matched in Brazil.</i>

235
00:15:24,535 --> 00:15:27,902
<i>This has made us
one of the most efficient</i>

236
00:15:28,105 --> 00:15:30,505
<i>urban combat units in the world.</i>

237
00:15:35,847 --> 00:15:41,251
<i>We are certainly better
than any American soldier.</i>

238
00:15:41,452 --> 00:15:46,947
<i>Our confrontations happen
within 10 meters, 15 meters.</i>

239
00:15:48,292 --> 00:15:50,317
SOLDIER MILTON BOPE
Our combat is real.

240
00:15:52,930 --> 00:15:55,125
<i>In the favela,
there are very narrow alleys.</i>

241
00:15:55,333 --> 00:15:58,029
<i>It's rare to find a spot
where 2 shooters</i>

242
00:15:58,236 --> 00:16:02,070
<i>can work side by side.
The 1st man shoots kneeling down.</i>

243
00:16:02,273 --> 00:16:06,676
<i>The second shoots over him,
using his back as support.</i>

244
00:16:06,878 --> 00:16:08,004
Attention!

245
00:16:08,212 --> 00:16:09,236
Fire!

246
00:16:18,756 --> 00:16:22,157
If I see the police, I try to run.
If I can't, I shoot.

247
00:16:22,360 --> 00:16:24,191
For instance,
I'm here selling dope.

248
00:16:24,395 --> 00:16:26,989
If I see the police,
I try to escape.

249
00:16:27,198 --> 00:16:30,690
<i>If I can't, I'll shoot.
I won't let them shoot me first.</i>

250
00:16:30,902 --> 00:16:32,233
<i>I'll get them first.</i>

251
00:16:32,436 --> 00:16:35,530
<i>I won't let them hit me.
They'd kill me.</i>

252
00:16:35,740 --> 00:16:37,605
<i>When we kill the enemy,
we use fireworks.</i>

253
00:16:38,242 --> 00:16:41,700
<i>We celebrate and everything.
We have a party.</i>

254
00:16:41,913 --> 00:16:45,076
It's a victory.
Isn't that worth celebrating?

255
00:16:45,283 --> 00:16:50,346
To kill the enemy is a victory.
Terceiro Comando, for example.

256
00:16:55,660 --> 00:16:58,629
<i>As a minor, I escaped 14 times,</i>

257
00:16:58,829 --> 00:17:01,730
<i>just from one detention
home called Padre Severino.</i>

258
00:17:01,999 --> 00:17:05,833
From another one,
I escaped another 7 times.

259
00:17:06,037 --> 00:17:10,098
When I turned 18,
I was arrested by the 10th Precinct.

260
00:17:10,308 --> 00:17:13,038
I stayed in jail for 9 months
and escaped.

261
00:17:13,244 --> 00:17:17,203
I was free for a month
and got arrested again.

262
00:17:17,415 --> 00:17:21,613
I stayed in jail for another
6 months and escaped again.

263
00:17:21,819 --> 00:17:26,984
Then, I was arrested and
sentenced to 9 years in prison.

264
00:17:27,191 --> 00:17:28,954
They sent me to Polinter,

265
00:17:29,160 --> 00:17:31,390
Água Santa, and so on.

266
00:17:31,596 --> 00:17:33,826
Then, I finally reached
the top security prison in Ilha Grande

267
00:17:34,031 --> 00:17:36,329
<i>I could only achieve
freedom by my own means,</i>

268
00:17:36,534 --> 00:17:40,231
<i>and God's help,
this is by escaping again.</i>

269
00:17:40,438 --> 00:17:45,068
<i>I escaped for the 3rd time.
I was free for only a month.</i>

270
00:17:45,276 --> 00:17:48,712
I was arrested again
under other charges.

271
00:17:48,913 --> 00:17:52,508
I went to jail and suffered
all of that again.

272
00:17:52,717 --> 00:17:55,481
I spent another 2 years
or so in prison.

273
00:17:55,686 --> 00:17:59,520
I was even angrier.
I wanted to lose my life.

274
00:17:59,724 --> 00:18:04,320
I tried to regain my freedom
and here I am, thank God.

275
00:18:08,599 --> 00:18:10,464
What do you do
when you are working?

276
00:18:10,668 --> 00:18:13,603
LICO - 13 YEARS OLD
I watch for the cops.

277
00:18:13,804 --> 00:18:15,499
-Do you carry guns?
-What?

278
00:18:15,706 --> 00:18:18,436
-Have you carried guns?
-Yes.

279
00:18:18,643 --> 00:18:20,668
How about you?
How far did you get in school?

280
00:18:20,878 --> 00:18:23,506
LEANDRO - 14 YEARS OLD
I quit after the 3rd grade.

281
00:18:24,248 --> 00:18:26,182
Can you read?

282
00:18:26,384 --> 00:18:28,875
Not really. I get by.

283
00:18:29,687 --> 00:18:30,984
How was your first mission?

284
00:18:31,188 --> 00:18:33,520
It was cool.

285
00:18:34,258 --> 00:18:37,091
-What did you do?
-I sold drugs.

286
00:18:37,862 --> 00:18:41,764
My first mission was robbery
on the streets.

287
00:18:41,966 --> 00:18:45,299
What do you feel
when you do that?

288
00:18:45,503 --> 00:18:48,995
I feel the desire to steal
from the person.

289
00:18:49,640 --> 00:18:51,904
-Are you afraid you'll die young?
-What?

290
00:18:52,109 --> 00:18:57,513
-Are you afraid you'll die young?
-We're all going to die someday, right?

291
00:18:58,382 --> 00:19:01,943
<i>What makes a young
person go into that?</i>

292
00:19:02,086 --> 00:19:05,317
<i>This generation,
born in the favela,</i>

293
00:19:05,523 --> 00:19:09,823
<i>which is a third generation,
wants to prove itself</i>

294
00:19:10,027 --> 00:19:11,858
<i>for the entire city.</i>

295
00:19:12,163 --> 00:19:14,563
I think the organization
offers that to them.

296
00:19:14,765 --> 00:19:16,596
ITAMAR SILVA - COMMUNITY LEADER
It offers to the boy the respect he

297
00:19:16,801 --> 00:19:22,330
doesn't get when he chooses to be
a delivery boy for a drugstore.

298
00:19:22,540 --> 00:19:27,603
<i>When he opens the paper
and reads that, at a certain favela,</i>

299
00:19:27,812 --> 00:19:33,045
<i>a young man faced the police,
armed and wearing a ski mask.</i>

300
00:19:33,250 --> 00:19:38,347
<i>This feeds the pride,
the power he believes he has</i>

301
00:19:38,556 --> 00:19:42,993
<i>over a society that doesn't
recognize his true worth.</i>

302
00:19:46,630 --> 00:19:48,495
<i>The heart beats stronger, right?</i>

303
00:19:48,699 --> 00:19:52,567
POLICE HEADQUARTERS
Somebody says he is a success

304
00:19:52,770 --> 00:19:56,467
HÉLIO LUZ CHIEF OF POLICE - RIO
''Finally, one of us is somebody.

305
00:19:56,674 --> 00:19:58,801
One of us can buy
an expensive car.

306
00:19:59,009 --> 00:20:00,943
One of us is able to have
5 women.

307
00:20:01,479 --> 00:20:06,041
<i>One of our own made it in life."</i>

308
00:20:07,084 --> 00:20:09,848
I felt like I was
the king of the world.

309
00:20:11,021 --> 00:20:12,420
When was that?

310
00:20:12,623 --> 00:20:17,390
At the favela when I held
my first gun, I felt like that.

311
00:20:18,095 --> 00:20:19,392
Was it a good feeling?

312
00:20:19,597 --> 00:20:22,191
Yeah, sort of...
Women look at you.

313
00:20:22,399 --> 00:20:24,560
They flirt with you.

314
00:20:27,238 --> 00:20:30,207
<i>Women, especially
from down in the city,</i>

315
00:20:30,407 --> 00:20:34,605
seem to be attracted by young men
with heavy guns.

316
00:20:34,812 --> 00:20:39,681
They go nuts!
They enter even the poorest shacks

317
00:20:39,884 --> 00:20:40,908
to go to bed with them.

318
00:20:41,118 --> 00:20:43,643
Only men with guns are
entitled to go out

319
00:20:43,854 --> 00:20:46,687
with city girls.
If you don't carry a gun...

320
00:20:46,891 --> 00:20:50,349
-They don't even look at you.
-They ignore you.

321
00:20:50,561 --> 00:20:53,394
They are all blond and beautiful.

322
00:20:53,597 --> 00:20:57,260
The bigger the gun, the more
they want to get near them,

323
00:20:57,468 --> 00:20:59,459
<i>the more they want to participate.</i>

324
00:20:59,670 --> 00:21:00,864
I don't starve.

325
00:21:01,205 --> 00:21:03,673
My family doesn't starve.

326
00:21:03,874 --> 00:21:06,069
I walk around with good clothes
because, in this line of business

327
00:21:06,277 --> 00:21:08,609
you have to look good.

328
00:21:09,446 --> 00:21:13,405
<i>-Which jeans do you wear?
-Toulon, Company.</i>

329
00:21:14,952 --> 00:21:17,079
T-shirt?

330
00:21:17,288 --> 00:21:19,722
TCK, Cyclone,

331
00:21:19,924 --> 00:21:22,415
Toulon or Company.

332
00:21:22,626 --> 00:21:25,094
What kind of tennis shoe
do you choose?

333
00:21:25,296 --> 00:21:26,820
I choose Nike.

334
00:21:27,031 --> 00:21:30,262
-Which one?
-Nike, Reebok.

335
00:21:35,639 --> 00:21:38,369
<i>If you had been born in the favela,
what would you be today?</i>

336
00:21:38,576 --> 00:21:41,044
<i>What options would I have?
If I got a job,</i>

337
00:21:41,812 --> 00:21:44,747
I would have to work
12 or 8 hours a day

338
00:21:44,949 --> 00:21:46,974
to make U$ 60 a month.

339
00:21:47,184 --> 00:21:50,278
If I was to get into drug dealing,

340
00:21:50,487 --> 00:21:53,149
I'd make U$ 150 a week.

341
00:21:53,357 --> 00:21:55,086
So it's a good deal.

342
00:21:55,292 --> 00:21:57,760
Don't you think so?
For anybody.

343
00:21:57,962 --> 00:22:02,023
It's not an option if you've never gone
hungry. But if you have, it's a job.

344
00:22:02,166 --> 00:22:04,259
For the social outcast,
it is a good deal.

345
00:22:04,468 --> 00:22:07,869
People line up to get a job.

346
00:22:08,072 --> 00:22:11,132
<i>You might say it's not a job,
but it is.</i>

347
00:22:11,342 --> 00:22:13,333
<i>It's not an option, it's a job.</i>

348
00:22:13,544 --> 00:22:16,138
<i>They make more money
then their fathers do.</i>

349
00:22:16,347 --> 00:22:17,712
<i>They're suicidal.</i>

350
00:22:17,915 --> 00:22:22,511
He watches his brother die,
his cousin die

351
00:22:22,720 --> 00:22:26,212
because they were involved,
but he wants to get involved!

352
00:22:26,423 --> 00:22:27,617
Do you know why?

353
00:22:27,825 --> 00:22:31,420
Because nobody wants this
meager salary anymore.

354
00:22:33,797 --> 00:22:37,096
Drug dealing is a business,
an illegal business.

355
00:22:38,135 --> 00:22:42,435
They occupy an area
left vacant by the government.

356
00:22:42,640 --> 00:22:45,973
The government makes the favela
an area for outcasts.

357
00:22:46,176 --> 00:22:48,736
The minimal wage is
U$ 60 a month?

358
00:22:48,946 --> 00:22:51,506
The drug dealers pay
the kid U$ 150 a week

359
00:22:51,715 --> 00:22:53,342
and that kid goes to work for them.

360
00:22:55,452 --> 00:22:58,148
<i>They will choose it, of course.</i>

361
00:22:58,355 --> 00:22:59,845
PADRE SEVERINO INSTITUTE - FOR
JUVENILE DELINQUENTS 12 TO 18

362
00:23:03,227 --> 00:23:04,592
Hands.

363
00:23:04,795 --> 00:23:08,026
Turn them.
Lift your arms.

364
00:23:08,232 --> 00:23:11,395
Lift your balls.

365
00:23:11,602 --> 00:23:13,536
Lift one leg.
Now, the other.

366
00:23:13,737 --> 00:23:14,795
-Turn around.
-Open your hand.

367
00:23:15,005 --> 00:23:17,030
-Down.
-Turn. Open your mouth.

368
00:23:17,241 --> 00:23:20,108
-Get up. Open your mouth.
-Lift your tongue.

369
00:23:20,311 --> 00:23:23,769
Hands towards
the ground and down.

370
00:23:23,981 --> 00:23:26,108
Get you clothes
and come to this side.

371
00:23:27,117 --> 00:23:30,382
FÁBIO - 16 YEARS OLD
I was arrested because of marijuana.

372
00:23:31,088 --> 00:23:34,819
-Do you work for the dealers?
-No. I just got in trouble.

373
00:23:36,927 --> 00:23:40,055
Is this your first time in here?
Where do you live?

374
00:23:40,264 --> 00:23:44,200
I live at Nova Holanda.

375
00:23:44,735 --> 00:23:47,465
VINÍCIUS - 17 YEARS OLD
Who me? I was selling cocaine.

376
00:23:47,671 --> 00:23:49,298
-Do you work for the dealers?
-No.

377
00:23:49,506 --> 00:23:54,443
I got into this less
than 3 days ago.

378
00:23:55,112 --> 00:23:59,276
-Where did you sell it?
-At Morrinho.

379
00:24:01,418 --> 00:24:02,442
Is this your 1st time?

380
00:24:02,653 --> 00:24:04,712
NELSON 14 YEARS OLD
Yes, sir.

381
00:24:04,922 --> 00:24:07,618
-Why were you arrested?
-I was stealing.

382
00:24:07,825 --> 00:24:11,124
-Where do you live?
-On the streets.

383
00:24:14,398 --> 00:24:18,425
<i>When you are 18 and have a
clean rap sheet, will you stop?</i>

384
00:24:18,836 --> 00:24:22,431
I intend to stay in the favela.

385
00:24:22,639 --> 00:24:25,437
Would you like to get a job?

386
00:24:25,642 --> 00:24:27,371
I want a job dealing drugs.

387
00:24:27,578 --> 00:24:31,446
-Only dealing?
-I like the life.

388
00:24:32,349 --> 00:24:35,750
Why did you get into this?

389
00:24:40,157 --> 00:24:43,285
I saw a lot of suffering.
The police always wants

390
00:24:43,494 --> 00:24:47,260
to beat people up. They have
no respect. They don't care

391
00:24:47,464 --> 00:24:51,525
if they come after the dealer
and get the worker.

392
00:24:51,735 --> 00:24:54,260
They can't do their job well.

393
00:24:56,206 --> 00:24:58,231
LAW ENFORCEMENT

394
00:25:00,477 --> 00:25:04,379
MAURINHO 16 YEARS OLD
The policemen arrested me.

395
00:25:04,581 --> 00:25:06,208
They booked me and said
they were going to kill me.

396
00:25:06,417 --> 00:25:07,714
They shot me in the leg.

397
00:25:07,918 --> 00:25:10,216
I was squatting down.

398
00:25:10,421 --> 00:25:11,979
The policeman came
and said: ''Get up.''

399
00:25:12,189 --> 00:25:14,749
He pointed at my leg and shot it.

400
00:25:14,958 --> 00:25:16,619
MAURO 15 YEARS OLD
When they get us, they take our money

401
00:25:16,827 --> 00:25:19,057
and give us trouble on top of it.

402
00:25:22,099 --> 00:25:26,263
Everybody knows the biggest
crooks are not the criminals,

403
00:25:26,470 --> 00:25:30,270
but the cops.
If a cop arrests me, for instance,

404
00:25:30,474 --> 00:25:35,878
he'll try to get money
not to take me to jail.

405
00:25:36,080 --> 00:25:37,741
He's not making only his salary.

406
00:25:37,948 --> 00:25:43,284
If you had a good television
set or a good VCR,

407
00:25:43,487 --> 00:25:45,455
they would take it away.
They wouldn't even ask

408
00:25:45,656 --> 00:25:49,092
if you had proof that
you've bought it in a store.

409
00:25:49,293 --> 00:25:51,557
They'd say that it was stolen,

410
00:25:51,762 --> 00:25:54,424
<i>even when the owner
was an honest person.</i>

411
00:25:55,532 --> 00:25:59,332
I'll say to myself
The police are corrupt.

412
00:25:59,603 --> 00:26:05,473
<i>The institution was designed
to be violent and corrupt.</i>

413
00:26:05,676 --> 00:26:07,041
<i>And people think that's odd.</i>

414
00:26:07,244 --> 00:26:08,768
<i>Why do I say it was
designed that way?</i>

415
00:26:08,979 --> 00:26:12,005
<i>Because it was created
to protect the State</i>

416
00:26:12,216 --> 00:26:13,444
<i>and the elite.</i>

417
00:26:13,650 --> 00:26:18,019
I practice law enforcement
to protect and serve the status quo

418
00:26:18,222 --> 00:26:21,020
No beating around the bush.

419
00:26:21,225 --> 00:26:22,817
It keeps the favela under control.

420
00:26:23,026 --> 00:26:26,757
How do you keep 2 million
people under control,

421
00:26:26,964 --> 00:26:30,456
people who make US$ 60 a month,
when they make any?

422
00:26:30,667 --> 00:26:33,830
How do you keep all
the underprivileged

423
00:26:34,037 --> 00:26:36,665
...under control and calm?
-With with repression?

424
00:26:36,874 --> 00:26:38,774
Of course!
How else would it be?

425
00:26:42,279 --> 00:26:45,976
<i>When the policeman
climbs up to the favela,</i>

426
00:26:46,183 --> 00:26:49,084
he's prepared to be
aggressive with everybody:

427
00:26:49,286 --> 00:26:51,311
old people, kids...

428
00:26:51,522 --> 00:26:54,047
Once, I was inside my home
and the cop said:

429
00:26:54,258 --> 00:26:59,696
''Listen, I don't care if people
are crippled, blind or old;

430
00:26:59,897 --> 00:27:02,229
I'll just beat the
heck out of them.

431
00:27:02,432 --> 00:27:05,060
And I don't want anyone
to say anything.''

432
00:27:15,746 --> 00:27:19,614
<i>Sometimes, when a kid from
the community is arrested,</i>

433
00:27:19,816 --> 00:27:23,616
<i>instead of going back down
to take the kid to jail</i>

434
00:27:23,820 --> 00:27:27,153
<i>they climb the favela's hill
even higher.</i>

435
00:27:32,396 --> 00:27:37,800
<i>The women, mother, cousins,
sisters, have to follow</i>

436
00:27:38,001 --> 00:27:40,970
<i>to stop anything from happening.</i>

437
00:27:41,171 --> 00:27:44,299
<i>By then, everybody thinks
the boy is facing</i>

438
00:27:44,508 --> 00:27:47,102
<i>some form of aggression
or even execution.</i>

439
00:28:11,034 --> 00:28:13,730
<i>We follow them, we fight, we cry.</i>

440
00:28:13,937 --> 00:28:16,371
<i>They push us around
and ask us to step back.</i>

441
00:28:16,573 --> 00:28:20,373
<i>We don't, because we know
what will happen.</i>

442
00:28:34,391 --> 00:28:36,552
<i>Then, we stick to them.</i>

443
00:28:36,760 --> 00:28:39,888
<i>That way, they can't have
a moment alone with the boy</i>

444
00:28:40,097 --> 00:28:43,032
<i>and nothing will happen to him.</i>

445
00:28:57,247 --> 00:29:00,307
<i>They end upcoming
down with the boy,</i>

446
00:29:00,517 --> 00:29:06,012
<i>taking him to the precinct
to see if he's really guilty.</i>

447
00:29:13,964 --> 00:29:18,367
<i>Sometimes, cops don't come
to arrest. They come to kill.</i>

448
00:29:27,110 --> 00:29:28,407
<i>It's a political police.</i>

449
00:29:29,279 --> 00:29:31,873
<i>This is an unfair society.</i>

450
00:29:32,082 --> 00:29:34,983
<i>We are here to protect
this unfair society.</i>

451
00:29:35,185 --> 00:29:36,584
<i>The underprivileged is under control.</i>

452
00:29:36,787 --> 00:29:39,119
<i>He'll pay if he gets uncontrollable.</i>

453
00:29:48,065 --> 00:29:50,158
<i>At the favela,
things are very sophisticated.</i>

454
00:29:50,367 --> 00:29:53,859
<i>In South Africa, they put up
barbed wire. Here, we don't.</i>

455
00:29:54,071 --> 00:29:56,904
<i>"Don't complain.
Pay your taxes."</i>

456
00:29:58,975 --> 00:30:00,704
People are used to it.

457
00:30:02,646 --> 00:30:05,479
<i>They conform to it.</i>

458
00:30:09,553 --> 00:30:12,021
<i>The poor have TV sets
and watch them.</i>

459
00:30:12,222 --> 00:30:13,985
<i>When the soap opera is over,
they turn it off,</i>

460
00:30:14,191 --> 00:30:15,818
<i>and look at the favela</i>

461
00:30:16,026 --> 00:30:17,459
<i>What are they supposed
to reproduce?</i>

462
00:30:18,695 --> 00:30:21,960
There are not violent.
They stay inside.

463
00:30:22,165 --> 00:30:25,601
They are so stupid
they just stay inside.

464
00:30:25,802 --> 00:30:29,795
When they do come out,
they are told to go back,

465
00:30:30,006 --> 00:30:31,633
<i>and they do.</i>

466
00:30:36,713 --> 00:30:43,380
I like to stay at the São Conrado
Fashion Mall's veranda. Why?

467
00:30:43,787 --> 00:30:46,915
There's a country club and
the largest favela in Rio side by side.

468
00:30:47,391 --> 00:30:50,690
<i>If this country was a violent
place, how could that be?</i>

469
00:30:50,894 --> 00:30:54,762
<i>Would that be possible?
This is a tranquil country.</i>

470
00:30:55,098 --> 00:30:58,124
<i>The safety policy adopted is efficient.</i>

471
00:30:58,335 --> 00:31:00,860
<i>Now, the question is:
does the society</i>

472
00:31:01,071 --> 00:31:03,232
<i>want a police without corruption?</i>

473
00:31:03,440 --> 00:31:06,341
<i>It's easy.
I'm not speaking theoretically.</i>

474
00:31:06,710 --> 00:31:11,374
I've worked in the interior
with squads of 30 men

475
00:31:11,581 --> 00:31:13,572
who wouldn't touch bribes.

476
00:31:13,784 --> 00:31:17,185
The first 2 months were great.

477
00:31:17,387 --> 00:31:22,222
The chief warden controlled
the town's drug deal operation.

478
00:31:22,426 --> 00:31:24,519
The town was in a state of panic.

479
00:31:24,728 --> 00:31:27,526
We got there with 30 honest men.

480
00:31:27,731 --> 00:31:30,097
We were cheered for 2 months.

481
00:31:30,300 --> 00:31:34,498
On the 3rd. month, the supermarket
owner's bodyguard

482
00:31:34,704 --> 00:31:39,141
slapped a kid who was
stealing a bottle of liquor.

483
00:31:39,342 --> 00:31:41,708
The kid and the bodyguard
were arrested.

484
00:31:41,912 --> 00:31:44,779
The supermarket owner said:
''Sir, he is a thief.''

485
00:31:44,981 --> 00:31:48,348
We said: ''But the bodyguard
can't hit a thief.''

486
00:31:48,552 --> 00:31:50,247
They were both booked.

487
00:31:50,454 --> 00:31:53,355
Then, social clubs
wouldn't invite me anymore

488
00:31:53,557 --> 00:31:57,550
for the Wednesday
night dinners.

489
00:31:57,761 --> 00:31:59,285
They stopped doing that...

490
00:31:59,496 --> 00:32:03,159
Then, a rich farmer
committed a murder.

491
00:32:04,968 --> 00:32:07,198
He was booked.

492
00:32:07,404 --> 00:32:09,099
End of story.

493
00:32:09,306 --> 00:32:10,796
There was trouble.

494
00:32:11,007 --> 00:32:12,770
What was seen as nice
Was no more.

495
00:32:13,777 --> 00:32:16,746
<i>We pose a question to society:
is there a real interest</i>

496
00:32:16,947 --> 00:32:19,006
<i>in an honest police?</i>

497
00:32:19,216 --> 00:32:22,481
An honest police will act
like in other countries.

498
00:32:22,686 --> 00:32:25,746
You don't park in a forbidden area,
because you'll get a ticket.

499
00:32:25,956 --> 00:32:29,653
You don't drive through a red light
or draw a graffiti.

500
00:32:29,860 --> 00:32:31,350
You don't do anything wrong.

501
00:32:31,561 --> 00:32:34,655
<i>Let's say we operate both in the
favela and in the rich neighborhoods.</i>

502
00:32:34,965 --> 00:32:40,062
People will have to stop
sniffing coke at their chic parties.

503
00:32:40,570 --> 00:32:43,038
There would be search warrants
and doors getting kicked down

504
00:32:43,240 --> 00:32:46,767
at the beachfront condos.
Isn't that right?

505
00:32:48,178 --> 00:32:50,476
<i>This is an honest police.</i>

506
00:32:50,680 --> 00:32:55,617
<i>It doesn't have limits.
Will the society handle it?</i>

507
00:33:00,824 --> 00:33:03,588
It's people who can pay

508
00:33:03,793 --> 00:33:06,523
US$ 500 for coke who are making
our profit. Most of them are

509
00:33:06,730 --> 00:33:12,100
from the upper class. Poor people
can't spend US$ 500 in cocaine,

510
00:33:12,302 --> 00:33:15,135
because his kid will
starve the next day.

511
00:33:15,338 --> 00:33:19,206
Rich people spend it,
because they can afford it.

512
00:33:21,444 --> 00:33:25,380
The middle class
supplies the money.

513
00:33:26,116 --> 00:33:30,610
With that money,
the dealers buy more guns.

514
00:33:30,820 --> 00:33:33,653
It's a vicious circle.

515
00:33:33,857 --> 00:33:37,691
<i>-The middle class...
-The are also the enemy.</i>

516
00:33:37,894 --> 00:33:41,330
<i>In a later date,
they scream against the violence.</i>

